          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/ERCOT/report/2024/page_149.jpg",
          "page_num": 149,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e8160eb3-084e-4b87-8c6d-c92e38711fad",
        "score": 0.6371958,
        "text": "The document page is from the 2002 Annual Report by the Market Oversight Division of the Public Utility Commission of Texas. It presents data on local congestion costs for the year, totaling $212.19 million. These costs are broken down into several categories:\n\n- OOM Capacity (OOMC): $88.85 million\n- OOM Energy Up (OOME Up): $37.22 million\n- OOM Energy Down (OOME Down): $39.43 million\n- Resource Specific Up (instruction): $23.33 million\n- Resource Specific Down (instruction): $23.37 million\n\nThe page includes a bar graph (Figure 12) showing monthly local congestion costs from August 2001 to December 2002, with notable peaks in April, June, and August 2002. The text explains that OOME Up and Down costs are payments to Qualified Scheduling Entities (QSEs) for manual instructions or deployment instructions when there is no market solution. Resource Specific Up and Down costs are payments for local balancing energy when a market solution exists. Footnotes clarify exclusions and adjustments related to these costs.",
