          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2002/page_37.jpg",
          "page_num": 37,
          "title": "2002 Annual Report on The ERCOT Wholesale Market",
          "year": 2002,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d5a02cf0-cd34-4a1f-9af9-cebf8a9b041d",
        "score": 0.633626,
        "text": "This document page is an appendix section titled \"Statistics at a Glance\" from the 2024 State of the Market Report. It presents Table A2, which summarizes the monthly aggregate costs of various ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas) market settlement totals for the year 2024. The table includes detailed monthly totals in millions of dollars for different cost categories related to ERCOT market operations and ancillary services.\n\nKey points from the table include:\n\n- **Energy costs** fluctuate monthly, with the highest cost in May ($1,851 million) and the lowest in February ($482 million).\n- **Regulation Up and Regulation Down** costs are relatively low, generally ranging from $0.4 million to $5 million per month.\n- **Responsive Reserve** and **Non-Spin** costs vary, with notable peaks in May ($20 million and $72 million, respectively).\n- **ERCOT Contingency Reserve Service** costs also vary, peaking in May at $48 million.\n- The **CRR Auction Distribution** shows consistent negative values each month, ranging from -$124 million to -$158 million, indicating a cost or payout in this category.\n- The **Balancing Account Surplus** fluctuates monthly, with the highest surplus in January ($40 million) and lower amounts in other months.\n- **Emergency Response Service** costs appear only in April, June, October, and December, with the highest cost in October ($30 million).\n- **Revenue Neutrality Uplift** varies monthly, with a peak in May ($27 million).\n- **AS Imbalance Uplift** shows small positive and negative values, indicating minor adjustments.\n- **ERCOT Fee** remains relatively stable, ranging from $19 million to $31 million monthly.\n- **ERO Passthrough Fee** is constant at $2 million each month.\n- **Firm Fuel Supply Service** costs are present only in some months, with the highest in December ($12 million).\n- **Other Load Allocation** costs are minimal and fluctuate around zero, with some months showing negative values.\n\nOverall, the table provides a comprehensive monthly financial overview of ERCOT market settlement costs and ancillary service expenses for 2024.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/ERCOT/report/2024/page_150.jpg",
          "page_num": 150,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3794a822-3b20-487a-8191-8888b022af3b",
        "score": 0.6318035,
        "text": "The document discusses the 2018 electricity market outcomes, focusing on costs associated with operating reserves and reliability. The highest monthly average operating reserve adder was $7.19 per MWh in July, and the highest reliability adder was $0.54 per MWh in May. Ancillary services costs increased to $1.60 per MWh from $0.87 in 2017.\n\nUplift costs rose to $1.08 per MWh in 2018, up from $1.02 in 2017, totaling approximately $408 million. Major components of uplift costs include the ERCOT system administrative fee ($209 million) and ERS program costs ($50 million). The revenue neutrality allocation (RENA) increased by almost 40%, from $96 million in 2017 to $134 million in 2018. Figure 2 provides an analysis of uplift and RENA for 2018.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2018/page_41.jpg",
          "page_num": 41,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "59b3a720-6fec-478a-b3e8-d40a064bb476",
        "score": 0.6302744,
        "text": "The document page from the ERCOT 2014 State of the Market Report discusses Point to Point (PTP) Obligation charges and payments. It includes a chart comparing Day Ahead Charges and Real-Time Payments for 2013 and 2014. In 2013, the annual charge was $316.8 million with payments of $309.0 million, while in 2014, the charge was $398.8 million with payments of $524.5 million. Generally, except for 2013, payments to PTP Obligation owners exceeded acquisition charges due to higher real-time congestion compared to day-ahead expectations. The document also briefly mentions the Ancillary Services Market, which includes up regulation, down regulation, responsive reserves, and non-spinning reserves, noting that participants can self-schedule or purchase these services.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2014/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2014 State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Wholesale Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2014,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

