        "text": "The document page from the ERCOT 2009 State of the Market Report discusses payment protocols for units dispatched out of merit (OOME up or down) and other related instructions. \n\n1. **OOME Payments**: Units dispatched out of merit are compensated based on the difference between scheduled and actual output, with payments determined by ERCOT protocols considering unit type, size, natural gas price, and balancing energy price. The net payment is the difference between the formula-based OOME amount and the balancing energy price.\n\n2. **Avoided-Cost Level**: For OOME down, payments are based on an avoided-cost level specific to the generation type. If a unit's avoided cost is $15 per MWh and the balancing energy price is $35 per MWh, the OOME down payment is $20 per MWh.\n\n3. **OOMS and RPRS Instructions**: Units providing capacity under OOMC or Local RPRS instructions receive pre-determined payments based on unit specifics and market conditions. These units must offer available energy into the balancing market, with Zonal RPRS selected based on startup and minimum energy offer prices.\n\n4. **RMR Agreements**: Reliability Must-Run (RMR) units are compensated based on agreements, covering start-up costs, energy costs, and standby fees. Since 2002, ERCOT has managed RMR agreements with older units, with a strategy to retire them by 2008. However, two new agreements were made in 2009. The document references a figure showing uplift costs from 2006 to 2009.",
